  "prompt": "Why is it easier to walk down stairs than up stairs?",
  "response": "Walking down stairs requires more effort to control your descent and prevent falling, but it's physically less demanding because:\n\n1. Gravity assists your movement downward, requiring less muscular exertion compared to climbing up\n\n2. Going down stairs requires more precise balance and muscle control to prevent falling, which can feel more challenging\n\n3. Climbing up stairs works against gravity, requiring more energy and muscle strength to lift your body weight with each step\n\n4. Walking down stairs engages different muscle groups, primarily using eccentric muscle contractions (muscles lengthening while under tension) which can feel easier but can cause more muscle soreness afterward\n\n5. Descending stairs puts more stress on your knees and joints, which can feel less intense in the moment but may cause more long-term strain\n\nSo while walking down stairs might seem \"easier\" in terms of energy expenditure, it actually requires more precise motor control and can be more technically challenging than ascending.",
